Exactly — a separate print style sheet makes it simple to hand someone a hard‑copy record of their own reflections without reformatting manually.  
Here’s a lightweight set of rules you can drop after your main CSS or wrap in a `@media print` block.

---

### 🖨️ Print Style Sheet  

```css
@media print {
  /* Use a clean white page and readable font size */
  body {
    background: #fff;
    color: #000;
    font-size: 11pt;
    line-height: 1.4;
    margin: 1.5cm;
  }

  /* Remove navigation colours and shading */
  section, .closing {
    background: #fff !important;
    border: 1px solid #ccc;
    border-left: none;
    padding: 0.6em 1em;
    page-break-inside: avoid;
  }

  header, footer, aside {
    border: none;
    color: #444;
  }

  /* Hide buttons, dynamic messages, and anything interactive */
  .button-row, #statusMsg {
    display: none !important;
  }

  /* Tighten tables for paper */
  table th, table td {
    border: 1px solid #aaa;
    padding: 0.3em;
    font-size: 10pt;
  }

  /* Optional: print footer automatically on each page */
  footer {
    position: fixed;
    bottom: 0;
    left: 0;
    right: 0;
    font-size: 9pt;
    text-align: center;
    color: #555;
  }

  /* Page break rules for long entries */
  h2 {
    page-break-after: avoid;
  }
}
```

---

🟢 **How it behaves**
- Background colors and accent borders simplify to grayscale for easy printing.  
- Buttons, status messages, and other interactive elements disappear.  
- Margins and text size adjust for an A4/Letter page.  
- Footer disclaimer remains visible on each page if the browser supports fixed printing.

